    thinking: "**Defining the Core Mockery**\n\nOkay, I\'m now honing in on the central satirical target: \"vibe coders\" and their broken attempts. The handwritten notes give a good idea of the \"broken\" elements I need to emphasize. My focus is on exaggerating the disconnect between their imagined skills and the reality, especially in terms of their code and project outcomes.\n\n\n**Developing the Bad Website**\n\nI\'m now outlining key satirical features for the \"bad\" website, focusing on intentional design flaws and inside jokes. The idea of using Comic Sans is a great start, highlighting the poor design choices often associated with this coding style. I\'m aiming for a webapp that\'s laughably bad, showcasing how \"vibe coding\" might actually look in practice. I\'m thinking of incorporating memes about the visible OTP. It\'s becoming clearer what the visual focus should be.\n\n\n**Designing the Chaotic Site**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the specifics for the terrible website\'s design, thinking about clashing colors and bizarre font choices, specifically Comic Sans and Papyrus. I\'m considering using marquee tags, implemented with CSS, and off-center divs. I\'m also fleshing out the meme concepts.\n\nI\'ve got a growing list of bad UI and code jokes, like \"OTP in the UI/Console\" during a sign-up, console logs filled with useless messages, buttons that move away when clicked, and AI-generated \"fixes.\" My action plan is taking shape, and involves using Lucide icons to add a faux-modern touch to the chaos. I will also have a multi-section one-pager, including a comically insecure login feature.\n\n\n**Implementing the Broken Features**\n\nI\'m now implementing the satirical features in React, with intentional design choices that will make experts chuckle. I\'ve broken the app into manageable components: Hero, SecureSignup (featuring the visible OTP joke), BadCounter (the state management jab), and LGTM. The code structure directly mocks the \"vibe coder\" approach with modular files, while the content is intentionally silly. I\'m focusing on the \"any\" type and the bad counter state management to deliver the key message.\n\n\n**Adding the Satirical Details**\n\nI\'m now incorporating specific satirical details. I\'m imagining the website \"Powered by 14,000 unread AI prompts\". I\'m also adding a button that says \"Submit... eventually\", a console error displayed in the UI, inline CSS with bizarre values, and, of course, the use of `alert()` for standard interactions. I\'m focusing on the implementation tasks now.\n\nI\'m starting the implementation. I\'m editing `metadata.json`, adding animations to `index.css`, and creating new components: Hero, SecureSignup, and VibeCheck. I\'m then revamping `App.tsx`. I know I should peek at the files before making the edits.\n\n\n**Constructing the Components**\n\nNow, I\'m drafting the React components. I\'m focusing on the visual and functional satire. I\'ve started the structure with Hero, SecureSignup, and VibeCheck, crafting the \"SecureSignup\" with its visible OTP joke, and the \"VibeCheck\" with an unreliable counter. I\'m also preparing to add the CSS to use Comic Sans!\n\n\n"
