  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Developing Chaotic Animations**\n\nI\'m currently focused on developing the `SpaghettiLoader` component. My goal is to craft chaotic, overlapping animations to achieve a unique visual effect. I\'m also considering a phone verification flow, perhaps within a new or existing component. I need to iron out the details, specifically how to implement a user calling their own number for verification.\n\n\n**Implementing Phone Verification**\n\nI\'ve shifted focus to phone verification, deciding to integrate it within `SecureSignup`. The plan is to have users click \"Call me,\" receive an OTP, and then call themselves to verbally confirm it. I\'m currently implementing the `SpaghettiLoader` component and will add it to `App.tsx` after compiling and checking the phone verification flow.\n\n\n**Refining User Verification**\n\nI\'m now revising the phone verification within `SecureSignup`. Instead of sending an OTP via Twilio (which is currently not configured), I\'m prompting the user to call *themselves*. This is a quick and effective alternative to bypass external dependencies.\n\n\n**Updating Verification Process**\n\nI\'ve updated `SecureSignup.tsx` to include clear verification instructions. Users will now see the generated OTP and step-by-step guidance, instructing them to call their phone from another and whisper it to themselves. I\'m focusing on ensuring this alternative to a traditional phone verification process is user-friendly and clearly communicated.\n\n\n**Exploring AI Verification**\n\nI\'m now investigating an AI-powered blockchain verification. This involves exploring AI voice recognition to enhance security, aiming for a \"Bank-Grade Verification\" process. This would involve an updated user flow and new component for OTP, and phone inputs. I\'m focusing on the implementation details and how to integrate this advanced method seamlessly.\n\n\n**Refining User Interface**\n\nI\'m now iterating on the user interface for the verification process. I\'m focusing on the visual feedback and clarity of instructions within `SecureSignup.tsx`. The goal is to make the instructions for the \"call yourself\" verification step very clear. I\'ve focused on using visual cues like text formatting and color to guide the user to the OTP. I\'ve also added a bouncing animation on the feedback.\n\n\n**Designing Animation Effects**\n\nI\'m now integrating the visual feedback and instruction display within `SecureSignup.tsx`. I\'ve added a button that provides error feedback if the AI voice recognition doesn\'t hear the user properly, incorporating visual cues to guide the user to the OTP. I\'ve also focused on animations within `SpaghettiLoader.tsx`, aiming for custom animations with inline styles for Tailwind. I\'m exploring spinning and bouncing with adjustable durations and direction.\n\n\n**Crafting Core Visuals**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `SpaghettiLoader.tsx` component into the `SecureSignup.tsx` file and customizing the animations to be more visually engaging. I\'ve been experimenting with inline styles and Tailwind to achieve distinct and appealing effects within `SpaghettiLoader`. I\'m working on balancing the spinning and bouncing with adjustable durations and directions. I\'m also ensuring the visual design works with the rest of the application.\n\n\n**Enhancing Error Feedback**\n\nI\'m now focusing on improving the error feedback mechanism within the `SecureSignup.tsx` component. I\'m aiming for dynamic, visually engaging displays to highlight issues and guide users effectively, like the ones with the npm install error message. I\'m exploring animations and text formatting to ensure that errors are clear, concise, and informative.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 43
      nanos: 581213886
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
