  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Exploring \"Vibe Coding\"**\n\nI\'m currently mulling over this \"vibe coding\" concept. It seems to have gained traction recently, thanks to Karpathy\'s description. The idea of letting AI generate code without even reading it, just trusting the \"vibe,\" is certainly intriguing. I\'m trying to unpack the implications and potential applications here. This approach strikes me as potentially revolutionary, and also as somewhat risky.\n\n\n**Analyzing the Parody**\n\nI\'m now diving deeper into the \"vibe coding\" parody. The humor highlights potential pitfalls: unreadable code, dependency overuse, security blunders, and UI quirks. I\'m focusing on the \"Please Fix Component\" as a starting point to capture the essence of this coding style. The joke\'s effectiveness comes from mirroring real-world developer frustrations.\n\n\n**Constructing Mockups**\n\nI\'m now building out the parody\'s components, focusing on visual representation. First, I\'m working on the `CookieBanner`, a fixed banner that shamelessly exploits the user. Next, I\'m developing the `AI Chat History` component, showcasing a hilariously incompetent AI \"fix\" chat log. Finally, I\'m sketching out the `npm install vibe` component, a floating window that parodies dependency bloat. I\'m making sure to mirror real-world frustrating user experiences.\n\n\n"
