  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Usability Paradox**\n\nI\'m wrestling with the inherent contradiction. The user wants functionality, a usable website, but peppered with deliberate, aesthetic errors, a \"vibe coder\" effect. Currently, the design leans too heavily towards meme showcase, not enough towards real-world usability with a specific aesthetic. My focus is now on finding that balance, making it function as a real site while maintaining the \"vibe coder\" charm.\n\n\n**Refining Application Layout**\n\nI\'m now focusing on structuring the core app around a recognizable SaaS layout. My goal is to create a \"Vibe Productivity\" or \"Vibe Social\" feel, but with deliberately terrible UI/UX. The hero section now looks like a landing page, complete with a SpaghettiLoader for a loading state, a secure signup, and a bad counter. The challenge is making it usable as it is.\n\n\n**Designing Functional Pain**\n\nI\'m now integrating the \"VibeTask\" concept. The flow starts with a secure but terribly designed sign-up, complete with a phone slider. Next, the user faces a dashboard transition, then a SpaghettiLoader, followed by a task list. Task creation uses a BadCounter style and a Fleeing Button for saving. Usability is key, meaning the phone slider, OTP entry, and task-adding features must function, but the experience should be deliberately awful.\n\n\n**Integrating Terrible Assistance**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `PromptHistory` as a terrible AI assistant that offers awful advice within the app\'s flow. I\'m focusing on the login screen, with the secure signup and phone slider, which will flip `isLoggedIn` to true when the OTP is entered. The usable app, or \"VibeTasks\" SaaS is taking shape. I\'m still working on components with disappearing input fields and fleeing buttons. I\'ll need to rewrite `App.tsx` and other components to pull together the various, but cohesive, parts.\n\n\n**Implementing Task Awfulness**\n\nMy focus is now on the \"VibeTodo\" component, creating a legitimate-looking but truly awful to-do list. Adding tasks will involve a slider for urgency, with high urgency forcing a 5-second wait. Submitting has a 50% chance of duplication. I am also implementing a fleeing button for task submission and random task deletion, the core components of the dashboard layout post-login. I am also preparing the `App.tsx` and `SecureSignup.tsx` components to handle routing and login functionality.\n\n\n**Adding Task Vibe**\n\nI\'m now integrating a color picker for tasks that only accepts hex codes entered from memory; no visual picker is allowed. I\'ve broken the work into steps: modifying `SecureSignup` for actual user logins, creating the `VibeTodo` component, and reorganizing `App.tsx` to handle the new states. The `VibeTodo` component will manage `todos` with `id`, `text`, and `color`. It uses text and hex inputs, an \"Add by vibes\" button (assigning \"Fix production bug\" if text is missing). Deleting a task randomly deletes one with a \"Whoops\" message. Plus, the phone number in `SecureSignup` now uses the TerribleUI slider as part of a multi-stage process.\n\n\n**Developing Task Flow**\n\nI\'m now integrating the multi-stage signup with login for \"VibeTasks\". The signup has three phases: the phone slider (99999 slider), then OTP entry, and finally, successful login. I\'m focusing on making the `VibeTodo` component. This includes text input with a random background color as the user types. The \"Add Task\" button will be implemented with fleeing button logic. Task list checkboxes will appear to work, but actually change the state of a different task. I plan to use `PromptHistory` and `CopilotHallOfFame` as \"Documentation\" or \"Help/Support\" sections.\n\n\n**Refining Component Interactions**\n\nI\'m now refactoring `SecureSignup.tsx` to include the phone slider directly, merging those states. I\'ll pass an `onLogin` prop, to be invoked after authentication. I\'m also preparing for the transition between the landing page and dashboard. My focus is still on ensuring the awful UX functions as intended within a coherent overall flow.\n\n\n**Streamlining Awfulness Structure**\n\nI\'m now streamlining the \"VibeTask Planner\". The entire app will be a terrible but functional to-do list, emphasizing the user\'s desire for a usable website filled with \"vibe coder\" mistakes. First, users *must* sign up/log in through `SecureSignup`. Then, they access the `VibeTodo` dashboard, with a terrible `TerribleUI` as a profile settings module and \"Help/Support\" via `PromptHistory`. I\'m rewriting `SecureSignup` with a terrible phone slider as part of the process.\n\n\n**Crafting Todo Functionality**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the VibeTodo component, specifically a task name input. The goal is crafting a legitimate-looking to-do list that is truly awful to use, as the current state is still focused on the terrible features it will include. My thoughts are centering around the core functionality, as the prior components are working now.\n\n\n**Designing Task UI**\n\nI\'m now implementing the terrible UI for task due dates. It\'s a free text field with a confusing prompt to \"Enter Due Date\". The \"Add Task\" button flees on hover for the first three attempts, finally settling. Checkboxes randomly mark other tasks as done. The \"Delete\" button sometimes throws an unhandled rejection, but the task deletes. I\'m focusing on the component\'s functionality, so I\'ll write `VibeTodo.tsx` first.\n\n\n**Implementing Fleeing Buttons**\n\nI\'m now implementing the fleeing \"Add Task\" button logic within the `VibeTodo` component. I\'ve got the state for flee count, position, and the handler in place. I\'m focusing on the component\'s functionality, so I\'m also implementing a random toggle functionality on checkboxes. I am now working on the state updates.\n\n\n**Integrating Secure Signup**\n\nI\'m now integrating the secure signup with the phone slider into a functional process. I\'m focusing on the `SecureSignup.tsx` component, including an `onLogin` callback. My approach is to ensure a terrible, multi-stage signup process works properly before the terrible todo interface. The login state will be toggled by a 5-step login process, which will be the initial state. The phone slider will have a 99999 value.\n\n\n**Refining App Entry Point**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `VibeTodo` components into the main app structure to toggle between the landing page and dashboard view. I\'ve got the `SecureSignup` component, now with the phone slider, and I\'m updating `App.tsx` to handle the logic. My current focus is to ensure a terrible, but functional, multi-stage signup process works. My approach is to ensure it works before the terrible to-do interface.\n\n\n**Implementing Signup Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating the multi-stage signup process, complete with a deliberately broken OTP verification and a terrible phone slider in `SecureSignup.tsx`. The component now includes a form for the phone number, OTP request, and verification, each step designed to frustrate the user. I\'m focusing on the state flow to make sure the process advances, however absurdly, and that onLogin is actually called. I\'ll need to revisit the `App.tsx` component to make it the entry point.\n\n\n**Merging Signup States**\n\nI\'m now focusing on removing `TerribleUI` from `App.tsx` as its phone slider and button logic are being directly integrated into `SecureSignup.tsx`. My current task involves refining `SecureSignup`\'s integration, specifically ensuring the multi-stage signup process triggers the `onLogin` callback. Simultaneously, I will review `VibeTodo` design to streamline its implementation.\n\n\n**Refining VibeTodo Functionality**\n\nI\'m now refining the core \"VibeTodo\" component\'s logic. I\'ve integrated a basic add function, with the fleeing button. The todo list randomly adds a sparkle emoji. I am also working on adding the functionality for a separate task to be toggled, when a