terrible deletion function. I\'m focusing on ensuring it consistently throws an unhandled rejection, yet the task disappears. The aim is to deliver that specific, terrible UX in every environment. I need to make sure the delete happens regardless, for the \"functionality\" part of the usability paradox.\n\n\n**Refining UI Interactivity**\n\nI\'m now integrating the phone number UI with its accompanying logic into the registration flow. This is now fully integrated with the 99999 slider and a terrible \"Generate OTP\" button. This works as the first part of a multi-stage process. Next is the OTP entry, with a \"very secure\" indicator. I am now working on the login state integration.\n\n\n**Integrating OTP Security**\n\nI\'m now integrating the OTP generation process within the UI. I have now implemented the OTP generation, and the instruction that instructs the user to \"Whisper the\". This will continue to the second phase, in which the user needs to enter the value.\n\n\n**Integrating OTP Functionality**\n\nI\'m now integrating the OTP flow for verification. The UI now includes \"Whisper the\" instructions. The AI checks if `actualOtp` matches the OTP entered, for true verification. This is combined with the secure signup. I am now working on App.tsx to route to the main `VibeTodo` app on a successful signup.\n\n\n**Implementing Login Routing**\n\nI\'m now implementing the routing in `App.tsx` between the secure signup and the main \"VibeTodo\" app based on the `isLoggedIn` state. I\'m focusing on ensuring the secure signup process works as a prerequisite. After a successful signup or login, the app must route to the awful to-do list component.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing Application Structure**\n\nI\'m now putting together the core application logic and final components, after an extended development. I\'m focusing on ensuring seamless transitions between the terrible signup flow, the awful to-do list, and the \"Help/Support\" components. The application now implements all its terrible functionality, and will route to the main `VibeTodo` app on a successful signup. I am now finalizing the application structure.\n\n\n**Refining UI Cleanup**\n\nNow, I\'m removing the `TerribleUI` component entirely, since its functionality (slider and button) is now integrated directly into `SecureSignup` and `VibeTodo`, improving the overall workflow. This improves usability. This also cleans up code and removes redundancy.\n\n\n**Streamlining Code Structure**\n\nI\'m removing `TerribleUI`, integrating its logic into `SecureSignup` and `VibeTodo` to streamline the code. I\'ve eliminated unnecessary imports and streamlined the components. The next step is a focus on cleaning up the `App.tsx` and refactoring based on current implementation and removal.\n\n\n**Streamlining Code Cleanup**\n\nI\'m now focusing on cleaning up the core application. After removing the `TerribleUI` component, I\'m streamlining imports and component integration, and streamlining `App.tsx`, and all core logic. The code has been rewritten for usability.\n\n\n**Optimizing App Transition**\n\nI\'m now integrating the transition between a SpaghettiLoader and SecureSignup, making the loader a temporary element before the login form appears. My focus is ensuring a seamless, yet terrible, user flow from the splash screen to the signup page. I aim for minimal UI \"improvement\" and no functional enhancement.\n\n\n**Finalizing Core Application Flow**\n\nI\'m now concluding the application\'s core logic and final components. I\'ve focused on solidifying the terrible signup-to-VibeTodo flow, integrating \"Help/Support\" components as designed. The app now implements its intended awful functionality and is fully functional. I\'m finalizing the structure.\n\n\n**Refining Main Component**\n\nI\'m now focusing on refining the main `App.tsx` file for the application, ensuring all the core components are correctly imported and rendered in the intended flow. After reviewing the imports, I am updating the app.tsx file to render all components.\n\n\n**Integrating Component Design**\n\nThe core components are now integrated within `App.tsx`, and I\'ve focused on ensuring the overall flow is working as expected. I\'ve been reworking all components to make sure the app works as intended. I\'m focusing on the awful signup and terrible task components that make the core of the app.\n\n\n**Implementing App Navigation**\n\nI\'m now integrating the awful app flow, with a SpaghettiLoader before `SecureSignup`. I\'m working on the awful state management for `isLoading` and `isLoggedIn`, which determine what the user sees. The `App.tsx` file is where I\'m putting it all together, and the goal is to have the worst possible login, with a very functional terrible VibeTodo component.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing File Integration**\n\nI\'m now generating all files for a final app render: `VibeTodo.tsx`, overwriting `SecureSignup.tsx`, and rewriting `App.tsx` as well. Each file is an example of terrible but functional usability for an awful VibeTask. I\'m making sure these components align with the final product.\n\n\n**Finalizing User Experience**\n\nI\'ve got the login flow, terrible components, and routing finalized within `App.tsx`. The goal is to maximize terrible function. The app is complete, integrating the awful signup, SpaghettiLoader, and \"VibeTodo.\" The user experience is now a terrible, but complete flow.\n\n\n**Finalizing Deployment Configuration**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the final tweaks. I\'ve integrated all core functions, optimized the awful UI, and refined routing. The secure signup, SpaghettiLoader, and \"VibeTodo\" components are now working in concert. I\'m reviewing the final deployment configuration and ensuring everything runs terribly, yet functionally, as planned.\n\n\n**Finalizing Project Integration**\n\nI\'m now integrating the final, awful product, from component design, and app structure, to deployment configuration. The aim is a terrible, but complete user experience that is also fully functional. The login flow, spaghetti loader, and \"VibeTodo\" are working together. I am making it all into a terrible but seamless flow.\n\n\n**Finalizing Awful Backend**\n\nI\'m now integrating the final \"backend\" logic using local storage, a `.txt` file for data, a global window object for state, and testing in production. My focus is on making it a truly terrible backend, yet functional within the app\'s overall awful design. I\'m focusing on those awful components.\n\n\n**Executing Final Actions**\n\nNow, I\'m executing the file operations: deleting `TerribleUI.tsx`, overwriting `VibeTodo.tsx`, `SecureSignup.tsx`, and `App.tsx`. After that, I will compile the applet, all to solidify the final structure and integration, despite the app\'s terrible core design.\n\n\n"
